Simple web stack
================

A user wants to access the website www.foobar.com from a browser.

1. The user types https://www.foobar.com in the browser.
2. The browser asks DNS to translate www.foobar.com into an IP address.
3. The DNS zone for foobar.com has a www record that points to 8.8.8.8.
4. The browser connects to the server at 8.8.8.8 using HTTP or HTTPS over TCP/IP.
5. Nginx receives the request on the server.
6. If the request is for a static file, Nginx can serve it directly.
7. If the request needs dynamic content, Nginx forwards it to the application server.
8. The application server runs the application code from the application files.
9. If data is needed, the application server queries the MySQL database.
10. The application server sends the response back to Nginx.
11. Nginx sends the final HTTP response back to the user's browser.

Infrastructure
--------------

Domain name:

    foobar.com

DNS record:

    www.foobar.com -> 8.8.8.8

Server:

    IP address: 8.8.8.8

    Components:
        - Nginx web server
        - Application server
        - Application files, which are the website code base
        - MySQL database

What each component does
-----------------------

A server is a physical or virtual machine that provides services to other
computers over a network. In this infrastructure, one server hosts every part
needed to run the website.

The domain name foobar.com is a human-readable name for the website. It lets
users access the site with a name instead of typing the server IP address
directly.

The www record in www.foobar.com is a DNS A record in this design, because it
maps the hostname www.foobar.com to the IPv4 address 8.8.8.8.

The web server, Nginx, receives HTTP or HTTPS requests from users. It serves
static files when possible and forwards dynamic requests to the application
server.

The application server runs the website's backend logic. It executes the
application code, builds dynamic pages or API responses, and communicates with
the database when data is required.

The application files are the code base of the website. They contain the source
code, templates, configuration, and other files needed by the application
server.

The database, MySQL, stores persistent data such as users, posts, products,
sessions, or any information the website needs to keep after a request ends.

The server communicates with the user's computer using the TCP/IP network
protocol suite. The website traffic itself is carried with HTTP or HTTPS.

Issues with this infrastructure
-------------------------------

SPOF:

    This design has a single point of failure. If the only server goes down,
    the web server, application server, application files, and database all
    become unavailable. The website is completely down.

Downtime during maintenance:

    Because everything runs on one server, maintenance can cause downtime. For
    example, deploying new code or restarting Nginx can temporarily make the
    website unavailable to users.

Cannot scale well:

    This infrastructure cannot handle too much incoming traffic. The web
    server, application server, and database all compete for the same CPU,
    memory, disk, and network resources. If traffic grows, there is no load
    balancer and no additional server to share the work.
